<L>If thou for&s;ak'&s;t me, how may I</L>
<L>Hope cheri&s;h in this bleeding heart?</L></Q></P>
<P>The expre&s;&s;ion, the marked tenderne&s;s&punc; with which &s;he &s;ang, were &s;ufficient proofs that Caroline's complaint had reference to a real, not an imaginary lover. But who was this lover? Was it Lindorf? Was it Wal&s;tein? Diffidence and doubt again po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed his hea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">; he looks, he li&s;tens, and pre&s;ently the &s;hadowy plea&s;ure of doubt it&s;elf vani&s;hes. Caroline laid her guitar in her lap, and untied a black <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">bband which &s;he always wore around her neck. Till then the Count had &s;uppo&s;ed it was only an ornament; but he &s;aw with &s;urpri&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> minia|ture picture was pendant to it, and which Caroline had always carried concealed in her bo&s;om. Too far off to di&s;tingui&s;h the features, he yet could &s;ee, as &s;he put it to the candle, that it was the uniform of an officer in the Pru&s;&s;ian guards; it was therefore, the uniform and the portrait of Lindorf! Caroline, at fir&s;t, fixed her eyes upon it, then pre&s;&s;ed it to her heart, and next to her lips, with extreme pa&s;&s;ion. The tears ran down her cheeks, and fell upon the picture; &s;he carefully wiped them off, again looked and &s;ighed, laid it on the table, took up her guitar and &s;ang another &s;tanza of the &s;ame &s;ong, which the Count di&s;tinctly heard.</P>
